      = {{bk|ESP|1945}} 118\u201332 {{bk-rt|LBY|1951}}<br>([[Madrid]], Spain; 9 May 1963)\n| largest_loss      = {{bk|USSR}} 118\u201358 {{bk-rt|ESP|1945}}<br>([[Essen]], West Germany; 12 September 1971)\n| medaltemplates    =\n{{MedalCount|total=yes\n|[[Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]|0|3|1\n|[[FIBA World Cup]]|2|0|0\n|[[EuroBasket]]|3|6|4\n|[[Basketball at the Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]]|3|4|1\n}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles]]|[[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2008 Summer Olympics|2008 Beijing]]|[[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London]]|[[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro]]|[[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2006 FIBA World Championship|2006 Japan]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2019 China]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket 2009|2009 Poland]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Eurobasket 2011|2011 Lithuania]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[Eurobasket 2015|2015 France]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[EuroBasket 1935|1935 Switzerland]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[EuroBasket 1973|1973 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[EuroBasket 1983|1983 France]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[EuroBasket 1999|1999 France]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[EuroBasket 2003|2003 Sweden]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[EuroBasket 2007|2007 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[EuroBasket 1991|1991 Italy]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[EuroBasket 2001|2001 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Eurobasket 2013|2013 Slovenia]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Eurobasket 2017|2017 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1955 Mediterranean Games|1955 Spain]]|[[Basketball at the 1955 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1997 Mediterranean Games|1997 Italy]]|[[Basketball at the 1997 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2001 Mediterranean Games|2001 Tunisia]]|[[Basketball at the 2001 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1951 Mediterranean Games|1951 Egypt]]|[[Basketball at the 1951 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1959 Mediterranean Games|1959 Lebanon]]|[[Basketball at the 1959 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1963 Mediterranean Games|1963 Italy]]|[[Basketball at the 1963 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[1987 Mediterranean Games|1987 Syria]]|[[Basketball at the 1987 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2005 Mediterranean Games|2005 Spain]]|[[Basketball at the 2005 Mediterranean Games|Team]]}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Spain national basketball team''' ({{lang-es|link=no|Selecci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola de Baloncesto}}) represents [[Spain]] in men's international [[basketball]] competition. They are managed by the [[Spanish Basketball Federation]], the governing body for [[basketball in Spain]].\n\nSpain has appeared 32 times at the [[EuroBasket]], winning three gold medals, six silver medals, and four bronze medals. They have also competed at the [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] 12 times, with three silver medals and one bronze medal as their accomplishments. They have qualified for the [[FIBA World Cup]] 12 times, winning it all twice, in [[2006 FIBA World Championship|2006]] and [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2019]].\n\nSpain is currently ranked 2nd in the [[FIBA World Rankings]], only behind the [[United States men's national basketball team|United States]].<ref>[http://www.fiba.com/pages/eng/fc/even/rank/p/rankMen.html FIBA.com \u2013 FIBA World Ranking for men<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Olympic Games===\nWhen Spain qualified for the [[Basketball at the 1936 Summer Olympics|1936 Summer Olympics]], where basketball was part of the games for the first time pito, expectations were high for the runner-up of the [[1935 EuroBasket]]. Unfortunately, as one of the favorites to win medals, Spain could not attend the Games because of the outbreak of the [[Spanish Civil War]] just days before the start of the Games.\n\nBefore the Spanish national team won the gold medal in the 2006 FIBA World Cup (see below), their greatest international success was reaching the final in the [[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Summer Olympics Basketball Tournament]] which took place in Los Angeles. The other finalist was the [[United States men's national basketball team|USA national team]] (led by [[Patrick Ewing]] and featuring a young [[Michael Jordan]]), which won the final and with it the gold medal. Spain, thus, took the Olympic silver medal.\n\nContinuing the success started at the 2006 FIBA World Cup, Spain again reached the final at the [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008 Summer Olympics]]. This proved to be a rematch of the 1984 Olympic final; this time, the USA team was led by [[Kobe Bryant]] and nicknamed the \"[[2008 United States men's Olympic basketball team|Redeem Team]]\". The Americans won after a remarkably close game 118-107. Four years later, at the [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012 Summer Olympics]] in London, the USA faced Spain for the gold once again. The Americans repeated as champions by the score of 107\u2013100, with Spain coming away with its third Olympic (and second straight) silver medal. During the [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2016 Summer Olympics]], Spain reached the bronze medal match against [[Australia national basketball team|Australia]], where they escaped with an 89-88 victory.\n\n===FIBA World Cup===\nIn the early years of the [[FIBA World Cup]], Spain struggled to establish a steady presence as a competitor. Between 1950 and 1970, the national team only qualified once. Then, beginning in 1974 Spain developed into a serious competitor and regularly finished among the tournaments top performers for years to come.\n\nAt the [[2006 FIBA World Championship|2006 FIBA World Cup]], the Spanish team finally achieved the ultimate victory, the greatest success in its history. The date was 3 September 2006, as Spain won the [[2006 FIBA World Championship Final|gold medal game]] against the [[Greece national basketball team|Greek national team]]. Held in the [[Saitama Super Arena]] in Japan, the game ended with a final score of 70\u201347. [[Pau Gasol]] was named the tournament [[MVP]], and [[Jorge Garbajosa]] also made the All-Tournament team. Shortly afterwards, the team were awarded with the 2006 [[Prince of Asturias Award]] in Sports.\n\nAt the [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2019 FIBA World Cup]], Spain achieved its second gold medal after defeating [[Argentina national basketball team|Argentina]] in the [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup Final|final]] by the score of 95-75. The spectacular play of [[Ricky Rubio]] during the tournament earned him the [[FIBA Basketball World Cup Most Valuable Player|MVP]], while [[Marc Gasol]] was named to the [[FIBA Basketball World Cup All-Tournament Team|All-Tournament team]]. After this victory, Marc Gasol became the second player in tournament history to have won the [[List of NBA champions|NBA]] title and the World Cup in the same year, the other being [[Lamar Odom]].\n\n===EuroBasket===\nThe first game in the history of the selection was a qualifier for the [[EuroBasket 1935]], where Spain defeated [[Portugal national basketball team|Portugal]] 33\u201312.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertaddigital.com/deportes/la-seleccion-espanola-de-baloncesto-cumple-75-anos-1276390230/|title=La selecci\u00f3n espa\u00f1ola de baloncesto cumple 75 a\u00f1os|publisher=Libertad Digital|language=Spanish|date=15 April 2010|accessdate=15 May 2015}}</ref> This event, which was held in [[Geneva]] in the summer of 1935, was the first [[EuroBasket]] game in history. Spain finished 2nd and qualified for the 1936 Summer Olympics in [[Berlin]] where basketball was introduced for the first time.\n\nAfter several tries, Spain won their first continental championship in [[EuroBasket 2009|2009]], defeating [[Serbia national basketball team|Serbia]] to become [[EuroBasket 2009 Final|European champions]]. The team repeated their success in [[EuroBasket 2011|2011]], taking out France in the [[EuroBasket 2011 Final|final]]. At [[EuroBasket 2015]], Spain once again reached the [[EuroBasket 2015 Final|title game]], and demolished [[Lithuania national basketball team|Lithuania]] in the process 80\u201363.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spain crowned champions at EuroBasket 2015|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/pr54-spain-crowned-champions-at-record-breaking-eurobasket-2015|accessdate=20 September 2015}}</ref> Two years after winning it all in 2015, Spain followed it up with another strong performance at [[EuroBasket 2017]], defeating [[Russia national basketball team|Russia]] to win the bronze medal match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Spain at the EuroBasket 2017|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/Spain|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> It marked the fourth time Spain won the bronze at the EuroBasket, as they also won it in [[EuroBasket 1991|1991]], [[EuroBasket 2001|2001]], and [[EuroBasket 2013|2013]].\n\n===Other events===\nBesides success at the \"Big Three\" events (Summer Olympic Games, FIBA World Cup, and EuroBasket) Spain has also had success at the [[Basketball at the Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]], where it has won several medals: three gold, four silver and one bronze.\n\n==Medal record==\nThe Spanish national team's medal record through the years:\n\n;[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]]:\n* Silver medals (3): [[Basketball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984]], [[Basketball at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2008]], [[Basketball at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2012]]\n* Bronze medals (1): [[Basketball at the 2016 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|2016]]\n\n;[[FIBA World Cup]]:\n* Gold medals (2): [[2006 FIBA World Championship|2006]], [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup|2019]]\n\n;[[EuroBasket]]:\n* Gold medals (3): [[EuroBasket 2009|2009]], [[EuroBasket 2011|2011]], [[Eurobasket 2015|2015]]\n* Silver medals (6): [[EuroBasket 1935|1935]], [[EuroBasket 1973|1973]], [[EuroBasket 1983|1983]], [[EuroBasket 1999|1999]], [[EuroBasket 2003|2003]], [[EuroBasket 2007|2007]]\n* Bronze medals (4): [[EuroBasket 1991|1991]], [[EuroBasket 2001|2001]], [[EuroBasket 2013|2013]], [[EuroBasket 2017|2017]]\n\n;[[Basketball at the Mediterranean Games|Mediterranean Games]]:\n* Gold medals (3): [[Basketball at the 1955 Mediterranean Games|1955]], [[1997 Mediterranean Games|1997]], [[Basketball at the 2001 Mediterranean Games|2001]]\n* Silver medals (4): [[Basketball at the 1951 Mediterranean Games|1951]], [[1959 Mediterranean Games|1959]], [[1963 Mediterranean Games|1963]], [[1987 Mediterranean Games|1987]]\n* Bronze medals (1): [[Basketball at the 2005 Mediterranean Games|2005]]\n\n==Competitive record==\n:''For the national team's all-time results against all nations, see [[Spain national basketball team head to head|Spain's head-to-head records & stats]] page''\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n===FIBA World Cup===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;font-size:90%;\"\n!colspan=5|[[FIBA World Cup|World Cup]]\n!rowspan=22|\n!colspan=4|[[FIBA Basketball World Cup qualification|Qualification]]\n|-\n!Year\n!Position\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|Pld|Games played}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=30|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[1950 FIBA World Championship|1950]]||9th||5||1||4\n|5||3||2\n|-\n|{{flagicon|BRA|1889}} [[1954 FIBA World Championship|1954]]\n|colspan=4 rowspan=5|''Did not qualify''